[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] where the indices *ℓ* and *m* (which are integers) are referred to as the degree and order of the associated Legendre polynomial respectively.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] This equation has nonzero solutions that are nonsingular on [−1, 1] only if *ℓ* and *m* are integers with 0 ≤ *m* ≤ *ℓ*, or with trivially equivalent negative values.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] When in addition *m* is even, the function is a polynomial.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] When *m* is zero and *ℓ* integer, these functions are identical to the Legendre polynomials.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] In general, when *ℓ* and *m* are integers, the regular solutions are sometimes called "associated Legendre polynomials", even though they are not polynomials when *m* is odd.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The fully general class of functions with arbitrary real or complex values of *ℓ* and *m* are Legendre functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] In that case the parameters are usually labelled with Greek letters.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The Legendre ordinary differential equation is frequently encountered in physics and other technical fields.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] In particular, it occurs when solving Laplace's equation (and related partial differential equations) in spherical coordinates.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] Associated Legendre polynomials play a vital role in the definition of spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] These functions are denoted $P_{\ell }^{m}(x)$ , where the superscript indicates the order and not a power of *P*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The (−1)*m* factor in this formula is known as the Condon–Shortley phase.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] This equation allows extension of the range of *m* to: −*ℓ* ≤ *m* ≤ *ℓ*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The definitions of *P**ℓ*±*m*, resulting from this expression by substitution of ±*m*, are proportional.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] with simple monomials and the generalized form of the binomial coefficient.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The sum effectively extends only over terms where $l-k$ is even, because for odd $l-k$ the binomial factor ${\binom {(l+k-1)/2}{l}}$ is zero.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The associated Legendre polynomials are not mutually orthogonal in general.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] Where *δ**k*,*ℓ* is the Kronecker delta.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The differential equation is clearly invariant under a change in sign of *m*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] (This followed from the Rodrigues' formula definition.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The integral over the product of three associated Legendre polynomials (with orders matching as shown below) is a necessary ingredient when developing products of Legendre polynomials into a series linear in the Legendre polynomials.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] For instance, this turns out to be necessary when doing atomic calculations of the Hartree–Fock variety where matrix elements of the Coulomb operator are needed.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] Dong and Lemus (2002) generalized the derivation of this formula to integrals over a product of an arbitrary number of associated Legendre polynomials.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] They are called the **Legendre functions** when defined in this more general way.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] $P_{\lambda }^{\mu }(z)$ and $Q_{\lambda }^{\mu }(z)$ both obey the various recurrence formulas given previously.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] More precisely, given an integer *m* $\geq$ 0, the above equation has nonsingular solutions only when $\lambda =\ell (\ell +1)\,$ for *ℓ* an integer ≥ *m*, and those solutions are proportional to $P_{\ell }^{m}(\cos \theta )$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] In many occasions in physics, associated Legendre polynomials in terms of angles occur where spherical symmetry is involved.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The colatitude angle in spherical coordinates is the angle $\theta$ used above.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The longitude angle, $\phi$ , appears in a multiplying factor.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] Together, they make a set of functions called spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] These functions express the symmetry of the two-sphere under the action of the Lie group SO(3).
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] What makes these functions useful is that they are central to the solution of the equation $\nabla ^{2}\psi +\lambda \psi =0$ on the surface of a sphere.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] for which the solutions are $P_{\ell }^{m}(\cos \theta )$ with $\ell {\geq }m$ and $\lambda =\ell (\ell +1)$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] For each choice of *ℓ*, there are 2ℓ + 1 functions for the various values of *m* and choices of sine and cosine.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] They are all orthogonal in both *ℓ* and *m* when integrated over the surface of the sphere.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] $Y_{\ell ,m}(\theta ,\phi )={\sqrt {\frac {(2\ell +1)(\ell -m)!}{4\pi (\ell +m)!}}}\ P_{\ell }^{m}(\cos \theta )\ e^{im\phi }\qquad -\ell \leq m\leq \ell .$ The functions $Y_{\ell ,m}(\theta ,\phi )$ are the spherical harmonics, and the quantity in the square root is a normalizing factor.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The spherical harmonic functions form a complete orthonormal set of functions in the sense of Fourier series.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] Workers in the fields of geodesy, geomagnetism and spectral analysis use a different phase and normalization factor than given here (see spherical harmonics).
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] and hence the solutions are spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] The Legendre polynomials are closely related to hypergeometric series.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] In the form of spherical harmonics, they express the symmetry of the two-sphere under the action of the Lie group SO(3).
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] There are many other Lie groups besides SO(3), and analogous generalizations of the Legendre polynomials exist to express the symmetries of semi-simple Lie groups and Riemannian symmetric spaces.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] Crudely speaking, one may define a Laplacian on symmetric spaces; the eigenfunctions of the Laplacian can be thought of as generalizations of the spherical harmonics to other settings.
[src:spherical-harmonics/associated-legendre-polynomials] By solving the Laplace equation in higher dimensions (with a potential that does not fall of $\sim 1/r$ ) Legendre Polynomials in higher than 3D can be defined.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] In physics, the **Clebsch–Gordan** (**CG**) **coefficients** are numbers that arise in angular momentum coupling in quantum mechanics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] They appear as the expansion coefficients of total angular momentum eigenstates in an uncoupled tensor product basis.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The name derives from the German mathematicians Alfred Clebsch and Paul Gordan, who encountered an equivalent problem in invariant theory.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] From a vector calculus perspective, the CG coefficients associated with the SO(3) group can be defined simply in terms of integrals of products of spherical harmonics and their complex conjugates.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The addition of spins in quantum-mechanical terms can be read directly from this approach as spherical harmonics are eigenfunctions of total angular momentum and projection thereof onto an axis, and the integrals correspond to the Hilbert space inner product.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] From the formal definition of angular momentum, recursion relations for the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients can be found.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] There also exist complicated explicit formulas for their direct calculation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The formulas below use Dirac's bra–ket notation and the Condon–Shortley phase convention is adopted.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Together the three operators define a *vector operator*, a rank one Cartesian tensor operator, $\mathbf {j} =(\mathrm {j_{x}} ,\mathrm {j_{y}} ,\mathrm {j_{z}} ).$ It is also known as a spherical vector, since it is also a spherical tensor operator.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] It is only for rank one that spherical tensor operators coincide with the Cartesian tensor operators.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] By developing this concept further, one can define another operator **j**2 as the inner product of **j** with itself: $\mathbf {j} ^{2}=\mathrm {j_{x}^{2}} +\mathrm {j_{y}^{2}} +\mathrm {j_{z}^{2}} .$ This is an example of a Casimir operator.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] It is diagonal and its eigenvalue characterizes the particular irreducible representation of the angular momentum algebra ${\mathfrak {so}}(3,\mathbb {R} )\cong {\mathfrak {su}}(2)$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] This is physically interpreted as the square of the total angular momentum of the states on which the representation acts.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] When two Hermitian operators commute, a common set of eigenstates exists.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Conventionally, **j**2 and jz are chosen.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] From the commutation relations, the possible eigenvalues can be found.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] These eigenstates are denoted |*j* *m*⟩ where *j* is the *angular momentum quantum number* and *m* is the *angular momentum projection* onto the z-axis.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] In principle, one may also introduce a (possibly complex) phase factor in the definition of $C_{\pm }(j,m)$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The choice made in this article is in agreement with the Condon–Shortley phase convention.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Here the italicized *j* and *m* denote integer or half-integer angular momentum quantum numbers of a particle or of a system.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] On the other hand, the roman jx, jy, jz, j+, j−, and **j**2 denote operators.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The $\delta$ symbols are Kronecker deltas.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] We now consider systems with two physically different angular momenta *j*1 and *j*2.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Examples include the spin and the orbital angular momentum of a single electron, or the spins of two electrons, or the orbital angular momenta of two electrons.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Mathematically, this means that the angular momentum operators act on a space $V_{1}$ of dimension $2j_{1}+1$ and also on a space $V_{2}$ of dimension $2j_{2}+1$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] We are then going to define a family of "total angular momentum" operators acting on the tensor product space $V_{1}\otimes V_{2}$ , which has dimension $(2j_{1}+1)(2j_{2}+1)$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The action of the total angular momentum operator on this space constitutes a representation of the SU(2) Lie algebra, but a reducible one.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The reduction of this reducible representation into irreducible pieces is the goal of Clebsch–Gordan theory.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The total angular momentum operators can be shown to *satisfy the very same commutation relations*, $[\mathrm {J} _{k},\mathrm {J} _{l}]=i\hbar \varepsilon _{klm}\mathrm {J} _{m}~,$ where *k*, *l*, *m* ∈ {*x*, *y*, *z*}.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Indeed, the preceding construction is the standard method for constructing an action of a Lie algebra on a tensor product representation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Note that it is common to omit the [*j*1 *j*2] part.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The total angular momentum quantum number *J* must satisfy the triangular condition that $|j_{1}-j_{2}|\leq J\leq j_{1}+j_{2},$ such that the three nonnegative integer or half-integer values could correspond to the three sides of a triangle.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] As an example, consider the tensor product of the three-dimensional representation corresponding to $j_{1}=1$ with the two-dimensional representation with $j_{2}=1/2$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The possible values of J are then $J=1/2$ and $J=3/2$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Thus, the six-dimensional tensor product representation decomposes as the direct sum of a two-dimensional representation and a four-dimensional representation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The goal is now to describe the preceding decomposition explicitly, that is, to explicitly describe basis elements in the tensor product space for each of the component representations that arise.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] For instance, from this formula, addition of three spin 1/2s yields a spin 3/2 and two spin 1/2s, ${\mathbf {2} }\otimes {\mathbf {2} }\otimes {\mathbf {2} }={\mathbf {4} }\oplus {\mathbf {2} }\oplus {\mathbf {2} }$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Note that some authors write them in a different order such as ⟨*j*1 *j*2; *m*1 *m*2 | *J* *M*⟩.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The recursion relations were discovered by physicist Giulio Racah from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 1941.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The Clebsch–Gordan coefficients ⟨*j*1 *m*1 *j*2 *m*2 | *J* *M*⟩ can then be found from these recursion relations.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The normalization is fixed by the requirement that the sum of the squares, which equivalent to the requirement that the norm of the state |[*j*1 *j*2] *J* *J*⟩ must be one.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The lower sign in the recursion relation can be used to find all the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients with *M* = *J* − 1.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Repeated use of that equation gives all coefficients.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] This procedure to find the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients shows that they are all real in the Condon–Shortley phase convention.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] A convenient way to derive these relations is by converting the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients to Wigner 3-j symbols using **3**.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The symmetry properties of Wigner 3-j symbols are much simpler.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Care is needed when simplifying phase factors: a quantum number may be a half-integer rather than an integer, therefore (−1)2*k* is not necessarily 1 for a given quantum number *k* unless it can be proven to be an integer.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Instead, it is replaced by the following weaker rule: $(-1)^{4k}=1$ for any angular-momentum-like quantum number *k*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Nonetheless, a combination of *ji* and *mi* is always an integer, so the stronger rule applies for these combinations: $(-1)^{2(j_{i}-m_{i})}=1$ This identity also holds if the sign of either *ji* or *mi* or both is reversed.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] It is useful to observe that any phase factor for a given (*ji*, *mi*) pair can be reduced to the canonical form: $(-1)^{aj_{i}+b(j_{i}-m_{i})}$ where *a* ∈ {0, 1, 2, 3} and *b* ∈ {0, 1} (other conventions are possible too).
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Converting phase factors into this form makes it easy to tell whether two phase factors are equivalent.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] An additional rule holds for combinations of *j*1, *j*2, and *j*3 that are related by a Clebsch-Gordan coefficient or Wigner 3-j symbol: $(-1)^{2(j_{1}+j_{2}+j_{3})}=1$ This identity also holds if the sign of any *ji* is reversed, or if any of them are substituted with an *mi* instead.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] Clebsch–Gordan coefficients are related to Wigner 3-j symbols which have more convenient symmetry relations.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] The factor (−1)2 *j*2 is due to the Condon–Shortley constraint that ⟨*j*1 *j*1 *j*2 (*J* − *j*1)|*J J*⟩ > 0, while (−1)*J* − *M* is due to the time-reversed nature of |*J M*⟩.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] For arbitrary groups and their representations, Clebsch–Gordan coefficients are not known in general.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] However, algorithms to produce Clebsch–Gordan coefficients for the special unitary group SU(*n*) are known.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] In particular, SU(3) Clebsch-Gordan coefficients have been computed and tabulated because of their utility in characterizing hadronic decays, where a flavor-SU(3) symmetry exists that relates the up, down, and strange quarks.
[src:spherical-harmonics/clebsch-gordan-coefficients] A web interface for tabulating SU(N) Clebsch–Gordan coefficients is readily available.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] A **multipole expansion** is a mathematical series representing a function that depends on angles—usually the two angles used in the spherical coordinate system (the polar and azimuthal angles) for three-dimensional Euclidean space, $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Multipole expansions are useful because, similar to Taylor series, often times only the first few terms are needed to provide a good approximation of the original function.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The function being expanded may be real- or complex-valued and is defined either on $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , or less often on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ for some other n .
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Multipole expansions are used frequently in the study of electromagnetic and gravitational fields, where the fields at distant points are given in terms of sources in a small region.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The multipole expansion with angles is often combined with an expansion in radius.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Such a combination gives an expansion describing a function throughout three-dimensional space.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The multipole expansion is expressed as a sum of terms with progressively finer angular features (moments).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The first (the zeroth-order) term is called the monopole moment, the second (the first-order) term is called the dipole moment, the third (the second-order) the quadrupole moment, the fourth (third-order) term is called the octupole moment, and so on.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Given the limitation of Greek numeral prefixes, terms of higher order are conventionally named by adding "-pole" to the number of poles—e.g., 32-pole (rarely dotriacontapole or triacontadipole) and 64-pole (rarely tetrahexacontapole or hexacontatetrapole).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] A multipole moment usually involves powers (or inverse powers) of the distance to the origin, as well as some angular dependence.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] In the first (more common) case, the coefficients of the series expansion are called *exterior multipole moments* or simply *multipole moments* whereas, in the second case, they are called *interior multipole moments*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Most commonly, the series is written as a sum of spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Here, the term C is the monopole; $C_{i}$ is a set of three numbers representing the dipole; and so on.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] In the above expansions, the coefficients may be real or complex.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] If the function being expressed as a multipole expansion is real, however, the coefficients must satisfy certain properties.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] While expansions of scalar functions are by far the most common application of multipole expansions, they may also be generalized to describe tensors of arbitrary rank.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] This finds use in multipole expansions of the vector potential in electromagnetism, or the metric perturbation in the description of gravitational waves.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] For describing functions of three dimensions, away from the coordinate origin, the coefficients of the multipole expansion can be written as functions of the distance to the origin, r —most frequently, as a Laurent series in powers of r .
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Multipole expansions are widely used in problems involving gravitational fields of systems of masses, electric and magnetic fields of charge and current distributions, and the propagation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] A classic example is the calculation of the *exterior* multipole moments of atomic nuclei from their interaction energies with the *interior* multipoles of the electronic orbitals.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The multipole moments of the nuclei report on the distribution of charges within the nucleus and, thus, on the shape of the nucleus.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Truncation of the multipole expansion to its first non-zero term is often useful for theoretical calculations.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Multipole expansions are also useful in numerical simulations, and form the basis of the fast multipole method of Greengard and Rokhlin, a general technique for efficient computation of energies and forces in systems of interacting particles.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The basic idea is to decompose the particles into groups; particles within a group interact normally (i.e., by the full potential), whereas the energies and forces between groups of particles are calculated from their multipole moments.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The efficiency of the fast multipole method is generally similar to that of Ewald summation, but is superior if the particles are clustered, i.e. the system has large density fluctuations.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Consider a discrete charge distribution consisting of N point charges *q**i* with position vectors **r***i*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] We assume the charges to be clustered around the origin, so that for all *i*: *r**i* < *r*max, where *r*max has some finite value.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The potential *V*(**R**), due to the charge distribution, at a point **R** outside the charge distribution, i.e., |**R**| > *r*max, can be expanded in powers of 1/*R*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Two ways of making this expansion can be found in the literature: The first is a Taylor series in the Cartesian coordinates *x*, *y*, and *z*, while the second is in terms of spherical harmonics which depend on spherical polar coordinates.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The Cartesian approach has the advantage that no prior knowledge of Legendre functions, spherical harmonics, etc., is required.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Its disadvantage is that the derivations are fairly cumbersome (in fact a large part of it is the implicit rederivation of the Legendre expansion of 1 / |**r** − **R**|, which was done once and for all by Legendre in the 1780s).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Also it is difficult to give a closed expression for a general term of the multipole expansion—usually only the first few terms are given followed by an ellipsis.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Removing the trace is common, because it takes the rotationally invariant *r*2 out of the second rank tensor.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] This expansion of the potential of a discrete charge distribution is very similar to the one in real solid harmonics given below.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] A spherical harmonic depends on the unit vector ${\hat {R}}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] This expansion is completely general in that it gives a closed form for all terms, not just for the first few.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] It shows that the spherical multipole moments appear as coefficients in the 1/*R* expansion of the potential.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] It is of interest to consider the first few terms in real form, which are the only terms commonly found in undergraduate textbooks.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Since the summand of the *m* summation is invariant under a unitary transformation of both factors simultaneously and since transformation of complex spherical harmonics to real form is by a unitary transformation, we can simply substitute real irregular solid harmonics and real multipole moments.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] In order to write the *ℓ* = 2 term, we have to introduce shorthand notations for the five real components of the quadrupole moment and the real spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Clearly the real notation becomes awkward very soon, exhibiting the usefulness of the complex notation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Consider two sets of point charges, one set {*q**i*} clustered around a point A and one set {*q**j*} clustered around a point B.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Think for example of two molecules, and recall that a molecule by definition consists of electrons (negative point charges) and nuclei (positive point charges).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The total electrostatic interaction energy *U**AB* between the two distributions is $U_{AB}=\sum _{i\in A}\sum _{j\in B}{\frac {q_{i}q_{j}}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}r_{ij}}}.$ This energy can be expanded in a power series in the inverse distance of A and B.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] This expansion is known as the **multipole expansion** of *U**AB*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] In order to derive this multipole expansion, we write **r**XY = **r***Y* − **r***X*, which is a vector pointing from X towards Y.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] This is the **multipole expansion** of the interaction energy of two non-overlapping charge distributions which are a distance *R**AB* apart.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The function *Y**m**l* is a normalized spherical harmonic.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] All atoms and molecules (except *S*-state atoms) have one or more non-vanishing permanent multipole moments.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Different definitions can be found in the literature, but the following definition in spherical form has the advantage that it is contained in one general equation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Because it is in complex form it has as the further advantage that it is easier to manipulate in calculations than its real counterpart.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] We consider a molecule consisting of *N* particles (electrons and nuclei) with charges *eZ**i*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] (Electrons have a *Z*-value of −1, while for nuclei it is the atomic number).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Particle *i* has spherical polar coordinates *r**i*, *θ**i*, and φ*i* and Cartesian coordinates *x**i*, *y**i*, and *z**i*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The (complex) electrostatic multipole operator is $Q_{\ell }^{m}\equiv \sum _{i=1}^{N}eZ_{i}\;R_{\ell }^{m}(\mathbf {r} _{i}),$ where $R_{\ell }^{m}(\mathbf {r} _{i})$ is a regular solid harmonic function in Racah's normalization (also known as Schmidt's semi-normalization).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] This has the consequence that selection rules hold for the expectation value of the multipole operator, or in other words, that the expectation value may vanish because of symmetry.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] A well-known example of this is the fact that molecules with an inversion center do not carry a dipole (the expectation values of $Q_{1}^{m}$ vanish for *m* = −1, 0, 1).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] For a molecule without symmetry, no selection rules are operative and such a molecule will have non-vanishing multipoles of any order (it will carry a dipole and simultaneously a quadrupole, octupole, hexadecapole, etc.).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The lowest explicit forms of the regular solid harmonics (with the Condon-Shortley phase) give: $M_{0}^{0}=\sum _{i=1}^{N}eZ_{i},$ (the total charge of the molecule).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Note that by a simple linear combination one can transform the complex multipole operators to real ones.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The real multipole operators are of cosine type $C_{\ell }^{m}$ or sine type $S_{\ell }^{m}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The definition of the complex molecular multipole moment given above is the complex conjugate of the definition given in this article, which follows the definition of the standard textbook on classical electrodynamics by Jackson, except for the normalization.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Moreover, in the classical definition of Jackson the equivalent of the *N*-particle quantum mechanical expectation value is an integral over a one-particle charge distribution.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Remember that in the case of a one-particle quantum mechanical system the expectation value is nothing but an integral over the charge distribution (modulus of wavefunction squared), so that the definition of this article is a quantum mechanical *N*-particle generalization of Jackson's definition.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] The definition in this article agrees with, among others, the one of Fano and Racah and Brink and Satchler.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] There are many types of multipole moments, since there are many types of potentials and many ways of approximating a potential by a series expansion, depending on the coordinates and the symmetry of the charge distribution.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Examples of 1/*R* potentials include the electric potential, the magnetic potential and the gravitational potential of point sources.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] An example of a ln *R* potential is the electric potential of an infinite line charge.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Multipole moments in mathematics and mathematical physics form an orthogonal basis for the decomposition of a function, based on the response of a field to point sources that are brought infinitely close to each other.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] These can be thought of as arranged in various geometrical shapes, or, in the sense of distribution theory, as directional derivatives.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Multipole expansions are related to the underlying rotational symmetry of the physical laws and their associated differential equations.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Even though the source terms (such as the masses, charges, or currents) may not be symmetrical, one can expand them in terms of irreducible representations of the rotational symmetry group, which leads to spherical harmonics and related sets of orthogonal functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] One uses the technique of separation of variables to extract the corresponding solutions for the radial dependencies.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] In practice, many fields can be well approximated with a finite number of multipole moments (although an infinite number may be required to reconstruct a field exactly).
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] A typical application is to approximate the field of a localized charge distribution by its monopole and dipole terms.
[src:spherical-harmonics/multipole-expansion] Problems solved once for a given order of multipole moment may be linearly combined to create a final approximate solution for a given source.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] In physics and mathematics, the **solid harmonics** are solutions of the Laplace equation in spherical polar coordinates, assumed to be (smooth) functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] There are two kinds: the *regular solid harmonics* $R_{\ell }^{m}(\mathbf {r} )$ , which are well-defined at the origin and the *irregular solid harmonics* $I_{\ell }^{m}(\mathbf {r} )$ , which are singular at the origin.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] This is convenient because in many applications the Racah normalization factor appears unchanged throughout the derivations.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] The addition theorems were proved in different manners by several authors.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] The regular solid harmonics are homogeneous, polynomial solutions to the Laplace equation $\Delta R=0$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] One particular basis of the space of homogeneous polynomials (in two variables) of degree k is $\left\{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{m}(x\pm iy)^{k-2m}\mid 0\leq m\leq k/2\right\}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] Note that it is the (unique up to normalization) basis of eigenvectors of the rotation group $SO(2)$ : The rotation $\rho _{\alpha }$ of the plane by $\alpha \in [0,2\pi ]$ acts as multiplication by $e^{\pm i(k-2m)\alpha }$ on the basis vector $(x^{2}+y^{2})^{m}(x+iy)^{k-2m}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] By a simple linear combination of solid harmonics of ±*m* these functions are transformed into real functions, i.e. functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] The real regular solid harmonics, expressed in Cartesian coordinates, are real-valued homogeneous polynomials of order $\ell$ in *x*, *y*, *z*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] The explicit form of these polynomials is of some importance.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] They appear, for example, in the form of spherical atomic orbitals and real multipole moments.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] The explicit Cartesian expression of the real regular harmonics will now be derived.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] The m dependent phase is known as the Condon–Shortley phase.
[src:spherical-harmonics/solid-harmonics] We list explicitly the lowest functions up to and including *ℓ* = 5.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] More intriguing techniques use SH to encode multiple functions—usually the global lighting environment and a per-vertex radiance transfer function.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] The generalized lighting equation involves, among other things, integrating the product of the incoming radiance and the BRDF over a sphere—something that is far too expensive for real-time rendering.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] But if the two functions are projected into SH coefficients, the integral of their product over the sphere is just the dot product of the two SH coefficient vectors.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Generating the per-vertex transfer functions and projecting them to SH space is still an expensive process, but evaluating them is almost trivial.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] More to the point, they can be evaluated correctly even if the lighting environment changes in intensity or orientation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Even the most complex ray-traced radiosity algorithm can be rendered in real-time with dynamically changing lighting.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] SH lighting using preprocessed coefficients produces results that are beautiful but limited.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Typically the lighting can change, or the lit mesh can be rotated, but the mesh can't be translated or deformed without requiring a new set of per-vertex coefficients.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] More recent techniques split the lighting equation into more parts and introduce techniques for updating SH components in real time or learn a transfer function which maps from shape deformations to updated per-vertex coefficients.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Representing scene illumination using SH is increasingly popular in the field of neural rendering as the illumination in a scene can be predicted and manipulated using deep neural networks.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In mathematics and physical science, **spherical harmonics** are special functions defined on the surface of a sphere.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are often employed in solving partial differential equations in many scientific fields.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The table of spherical harmonics contains a list of common spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since the spherical harmonics form a complete set of orthogonal functions and thus an orthonormal basis, certain functions defined on the surface of a sphere can be written as a sum of these spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is similar to periodic functions defined on a circle that can be expressed as a sum of circular functions (sines and cosines) via Fourier series.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Like the sines and cosines in Fourier series, the spherical harmonics may be organized by (spatial) angular frequency, as seen in the rows of functions in the illustration on the right.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Further, spherical harmonics are basis functions for irreducible representations of SO(3), the group of rotations in three dimensions, and thus play a central role in the group theoretic discussion of SO(3).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics originate from solving Laplace's equation in the spherical domains.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Functions that are solutions to Laplace's equation are called harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Despite their name, spherical harmonics take their simplest form in Cartesian coordinates, where they can be defined as homogeneous polynomials of degree $\ell$ in $(x,y,z)$ that obey Laplace's equation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In this setting, they may be viewed as the angular portion of a set of solutions to Laplace's equation in three dimensions, and this viewpoint is often taken as an alternative definition.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics, as functions on the sphere, are eigenfunctions of the Laplace-Beltrami operator (see Higher dimensions).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] A specific set of spherical harmonics, denoted $Y_{\ell }^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ or $Y_{\ell }^{m}({\mathbf {r} })$ , are known as Laplace's spherical harmonics, as they were first introduced by Pierre Simon de Laplace in 1782.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions form an orthogonal system, and are thus basic to the expansion of a general function on the sphere as alluded to above.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 3D computer graphics, spherical harmonics play a role in a wide variety of topics including indirect lighting (ambient occlusion, global illumination, precomputed radiance transfer, etc.) and modelling of 3D shapes.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics were first investigated in connection with the Newtonian potential of Newton's law of universal gravitation in three dimensions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Each term in the above summation is an individual Newtonian potential for a point mass.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Just prior to that time, Adrien-Marie Legendre had investigated the expansion of the Newtonian potential in powers of *r* = |**x**| and *r*1 = |**x**1|.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] where *γ* is the angle between the vectors **x** and **x**1.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The functions $P_{i}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ are the Legendre polynomials, and they can be derived as a special case of spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Subsequently, in his 1782 memoir, Laplace investigated these coefficients using spherical coordinates to represent the angle *γ* between **x**1 and **x**.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 1867, William Thomson (Lord Kelvin) and Peter Guthrie Tait introduced the solid spherical harmonics in their *Treatise on Natural Philosophy*, and also first introduced the name of "spherical harmonics" for these functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The 19th century development of Fourier series made possible the solution of a wide variety of physical problems in rectangular domains, such as the solution of the heat equation and wave equation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This could be achieved by expansion of functions in series of trigonometric functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Whereas the trigonometric functions in a Fourier series represent the fundamental modes of vibration in a string, the spherical harmonics represent the fundamental modes of vibration of a sphere in much the same way.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many aspects of the theory of Fourier series could be generalized by taking expansions in spherical harmonics rather than trigonometric functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Moreover, analogous to how trigonometric functions can equivalently be written as complex exponentials, spherical harmonics also possessed an equivalent form as complex-valued functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This was a boon for problems possessing spherical symmetry, such as those of celestial mechanics originally studied by Laplace and Legendre.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The prevalence of spherical harmonics already in physics set the stage for their later importance in the 20th century birth of quantum mechanics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The (complex-valued) spherical harmonics $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ are eigenfunctions of the square of the orbital angular momentum operator $-i\hbar \mathbf {r} \times \nabla ,$ and therefore they represent the different quantized configurations of atomic orbitals.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Laplace's equation imposes that the Laplacian of a scalar field *f* is zero.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] A priori, *m* is a complex constant, but because Φ must be a periodic function whose period evenly divides 2*π*, *m* is necessarily an integer and Φ is a linear combination of the complex exponentials *e*± *imφ*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The solution function *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is regular at the poles of the sphere, where *θ* = 0, *π*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Furthermore, a change of variables *t* = cos *θ* transforms this equation into the Legendre equation, whose solution is a multiple of the associated Legendre polynomial *Pm ℓ*(cos *θ*) .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, the equation for *R* has solutions of the form *R*(*r*) = *A rℓ* + *B r*−*ℓ* − 1; requiring the solution to be regular throughout **R**3 forces *B* = 0.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here the solution was assumed to have the special form *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) = Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For a given value of *ℓ*, there are 2*ℓ* + 1 independent solutions of this form, one for each integer *m* with −*ℓ* ≤ *m* ≤ *ℓ*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ is called a **spherical harmonic function of degree *ℓ* and order *m***, $P_{\ell }^{m}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ is an associated Legendre polynomial, *N* is a normalization constant, and *θ* and *φ* represent colatitude and longitude, respectively.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, the colatitude *θ*, or polar angle, ranges from *0* at the North Pole, to *π*/2 at the Equator, to *π* at the South Pole, and the longitude *φ*, or azimuth, may assume all values with 0 ≤ *φ* < 2*π*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In fact, for any such solution, *rℓ Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is the expression in spherical coordinates of a homogeneous polynomial $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ that is harmonic (see below), and so counting dimensions shows that there are 2*ℓ* + 1 linearly independent such polynomials.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] where the $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ are constants and the factors *rℓ Yℓm* are known as (*regular*) solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $r>R$ , the solid harmonics with negative powers of r (the *irregular* solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\setminus \{\mathbf {0} \}\to \mathbb {C}$ ) are chosen instead.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In that case, one needs to expand the solution of known regions in Laurent series (about $r=\infty$ ), instead of the Taylor series (about $r=0$ ) used above, to match the terms and find series expansion coefficients $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] If *Y* is a joint eigenfunction of **L**2 and *L**z*, then by definition ${\begin{aligned}\mathbf {L} ^{2}Y&=\lambda Y\\L_{z}Y&=mY\end{aligned}}$ for some real numbers *m* and *λ*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here *m* must in fact be an integer, for *Y* must be periodic in the coordinate *φ* with period a number that evenly divides 2*π*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, *L**k* + : *E**λ*,*m* → *E**λ*,*m*+*k* must be zero for *k* sufficiently large, because the inequality *λ* ≥ *m*2 must hold in each of the nontrivial joint eigenspaces.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The foregoing has been all worked out in the spherical coordinate representation, $\langle \theta ,\varphi |lm\rangle =Y_{l}^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ but may be expressed more abstractly in the complete, orthonormal spherical ket basis.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics can be expressed as the restriction to the unit sphere of certain polynomial functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Specifically, we say that a (complex-valued) polynomial function $p:\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ is *homogeneous* of degree $\ell$ if $p(\lambda \mathbf {x} )=\lambda ^{\ell }p(\mathbf {x} )$ for all real numbers $\lambda \in \mathbb {R}$ and all $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] We say that p is *harmonic* if $\Delta p=0,$ where $\Delta$ is the Laplacian.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, when $\ell =1$ , $\mathbf {A} _{1}$ is just the 3-dimensional space of all linear functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , since any such function is automatically harmonic.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For any $\ell$ , the space $\mathbf {H} _{\ell }$ of spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ is just the space of restrictions to the sphere $S^{2}$ of the elements of $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] As suggested in the introduction, this perspective is presumably the origin of the term "spherical harmonic" (i.e., the restriction to the sphere of a harmonic function).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, for any $c\in \mathbb {C}$ the formula $p(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})=c(x_{1}+ix_{2})^{\ell }$ defines a homogeneous polynomial of degree $\ell$ with domain and codomain $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , which happens to be independent of $x_{3}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This polynomial is easily seen to be harmonic.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] One source of confusion with the definition of the spherical harmonic functions concerns a phase factor of $(-1)^{m}$ , commonly referred to as the Condon–Shortley phase in the quantum mechanical literature.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This phase factor may be included either in the definition of the associated Legendre polynomials or in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but it should not be counted twice.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Some authors instead define associated Legendre functions without this phase factor.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] There is no requirement to use the Condon–Shortley phase in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but including it can simplify some quantum mechanical operations, especially the application of raising and lowering operators.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The geodesy and magnetics communities commonly use conventions in which the Condon–Shortley phase factor is not included in the associated Legendre functions or in the spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Several different normalizations are in common use for the Laplace spherical harmonic functions $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] These normalization choices are independent of the placement of the Condon–Shortley phase.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The disciplines of geodesy and spectral analysis often use the corresponding $4\pi$ -normalized harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The magnetics community, in contrast, often uses Schmidt semi-normalized harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For the phase convention used in this article, the complex spherical harmonics satisfy $Y_{\ell }^{m}{}^{*}(\theta ,\varphi )=(-1)^{m}Y_{\ell }^{-m}(\theta ,\varphi ),$ where the superscript * denotes complex conjugation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This equation also follows from the relation of the spherical harmonic functions with the Wigner D-matrix.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ are sometimes known as *tesseral spherical harmonics*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions have the same orthonormality properties as the complex ones $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ above.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}$ with *m* > 0 are said to be of cosine type, and those with *m* < 0 of sine type.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] With a different placement of that phase, the displayed signs must be changed consistently.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The same sine and cosine factors can be also seen in the following subsection that deals with the Cartesian representation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] See here for a list of real spherical harmonics up to and including $\ell =4$ , which can be seen to be consistent with the output of the equations above.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] From the analytic solutions for the hydrogen atom, the eigenfunctions of the angular part of the wave function are spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, the solutions of the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation without magnetic terms can be made real.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is why the real forms are extensively used in basis functions for quantum chemistry, as the programs do not then need to use complex algebra.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here, the real functions span the same space as the complex ones would.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, as can be seen from the table of spherical harmonics, the usual *p* functions ( $\ell =1$ ) are complex and mix axis directions, but the real versions are essentially just *x*, *y*, and *z*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] More specifically, it is the (unique up to normalization) Gelfand-Tsetlin-basis of this representation of the rotational group $SO(3)$ and an explicit formula for $R_{\ell }^{m}$ in cartesian coordinates can be derived from that fact.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] It suffices to take v and $\lambda$ as real parameters.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In naming this generating function after Herglotz, we follow Courant & Hilbert 1962, §VII.7, who credit unpublished notes by him for its discovery.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Essentially all the properties of the spherical harmonics can be derived from this generating function.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are, moreover, a standardized set with a fixed scale or normalization.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The factor ${\bar {\Pi }}_{\ell }^{m}(z)$ is essentially the associated Legendre polynomial $P_{\ell }^{m}(\cos \theta )$ , and the factors $(A_{m}\pm iB_{m})$ are essentially $e^{\pm im\varphi }$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have deep and consequential properties under the operations of spatial inversion (parity) and rotation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have definite parity.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] That is, they are either even or odd with respect to inversion about the origin.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Inversion is represented by the operator $P\Psi (\mathbf {r} )=\Psi (-\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] In terms of the spherical angles, parity transforms a point with coordinates $\{\theta ,\varphi \}$ to $\{\pi -\theta ,\pi +\varphi \}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Parity continues to hold for real spherical harmonics, and for spherical harmonics in higher dimensions: applying a point reflection to a spherical harmonic of degree ℓ changes the sign by a factor of (−1)*ℓ*.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Consider a rotation ${\mathcal {R}}$ about the origin that sends the unit vector $\mathbf {r}$ to $\mathbf {r} '$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Under this operation, a spherical harmonic of degree $\ell$ and order m transforms into a linear combination of spherical harmonics of the same degree.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, this is not the standard way of expressing this property.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The rotational behavior of the spherical harmonics is perhaps their quintessential feature from the viewpoint of group theory.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ 's of degree $\ell$ provide a basis set of functions for the irreducible representation of the group SO(3) of dimension $(2\ell +1)$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many facts about spherical harmonics (such as the addition theorem) that are proved laboriously using the methods of analysis acquire simpler proofs and deeper significance using the methods of symmetry.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ form a complete set of orthonormal functions and thus form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions $L_{\mathbb {C} }^{2}(S^{2})$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The expansion coefficients are the analogs of Fourier coefficients, and can be obtained by multiplying the above equation by the complex conjugate of a spherical harmonic, integrating over the solid angle Ω, and utilizing the above orthogonality relationships.
