[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* = 0, the spectrum is "white" as each degree possesses equal power.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* < 0, the spectrum is termed "red" as there is more power at the low degrees with long wavelengths than higher degrees.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, when *β* > 0, the spectrum is termed "blue".
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The condition on the order of growth of *S**ff*(*ℓ*) is related to the order of differentiability of *f* in the next section.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics are used to approximate functions on the sphere, and the order of decay of the power governs smoothness.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Let $\Pi _{n}(S^{2})$ denote the space spanned by spherical harmonics of degree at most n .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] with the norm taken in $L^{p}(S^{2})$ , or in the uniform norm when $p=\infty$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] The asymptotic behavior of $E_{n}(f)_{p}$ as $n\to \infty$ gives a quantitative measure of how well f can be approximated by low-degree spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is analogous to approximation by trigonometric polynomials in ordinary Fourier analysis.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the circle, smoothness can be measured by the decay of Fourier coefficients.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the sphere, smoother functions admit faster approximation by spherical polynomials, while conversely, sufficiently rapid decay of the approximation error implies smoothness.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] More precisely, Sobolev-type smoothness can also be described spectrally, since spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ are eigenfunctions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator with eigenvalue $-\ell (\ell +1)$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $p=2$ this relation can be stated especially explicitly.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus $f\in H^{s}(S^{2})$ precisely when this weighted sum is finite.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since $\ell (\ell +1)$ grows like $\ell ^{2}$ , higher Sobolev smoothness requires faster decay of the power in high degrees.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] which bounds the approximation error by the Sobolev norm.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] With the above power normalization, a decay estimate of the form $S_{ff}(\ell )=O(\ell ^{-\alpha })$ implies membership in $H^{s}(S^{2})$ whenever $\alpha >2s+1$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus sufficiently fast polynomial decay of the power spectrum implies differentiability, and decay faster than every power implies smoothness of all orders.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] A mathematical result of considerable interest and use is called the *addition theorem* for spherical harmonics.
