[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The values of c and $\gamma$ that result in non-zero terms in this sum are determined by the selection rules for the 3j-symbols.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Clebsch–Gordan coefficients are the coefficients appearing in the expansion of the product of two spherical harmonics in terms of spherical harmonics themselves.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] A variety of techniques are available for doing essentially the same calculation, including the Wigner 3-jm symbol, the Racah coefficients, and the Slater integrals.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Abstractly, the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients express the tensor product of two irreducible representations of the rotation group as a sum of irreducible representations: suitably normalized, the coefficients are then the multiplicities.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ can be visualized by considering their "nodal lines", that is, the set of points on the sphere where $\Re [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ , or alternatively where $\Im [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Nodal lines of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ are composed of *ℓ* circles: there are |*m*| circles along longitudes and *ℓ*−|*m*| circles along latitudes.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] One can determine the number of nodal lines of each type by counting the number of zeros of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ in the $\theta$ and $\varphi$ directions respectively.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\theta$ , the real and imaginary components of the associated Legendre polynomials each possess *ℓ*−|*m*| zeros, each giving rise to a nodal 'line of latitude'.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] On the other hand, considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\varphi$ , the trigonometric sin and cos functions possess 2|*m*| zeros, each of which gives rise to a nodal 'line of longitude'.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] When the spherical harmonic order *m* is zero (upper-left in the figure), the spherical harmonic functions do not depend upon longitude, and are referred to as ***zonal***.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Such spherical harmonics are a special case of zonal spherical functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] When *ℓ* = |*m*| (bottom-right in the figure), there are no zero crossings in latitude, and the functions are referred to as ***sectoral***.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] For the other cases, the functions checker the sphere, and they are referred to as ***tesseral***.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] More general spherical harmonics of degree ℓ are not necessarily those of the Laplace basis $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ , and their nodal sets can be of a fairly general kind.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The classical spherical harmonics are defined as complex-valued functions on the unit sphere $S^{2}$ inside three-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be generalized to higher-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as follows, leading to functions $S^{n-1}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **P***ℓ* denote the space of complex-valued homogeneous polynomials of degree ℓ in n real variables, here considered as functions $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **A***ℓ* denote the subspace of **P***ℓ* consisting of all harmonic polynomials: $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }:=\{p\in \mathbf {P} _{\ell }\,\mid \,\Delta p=0\}\,.$ These are the (regular) solid spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics of degree ℓ is a representation of the symmetry group of rotations around a point (SO(3)) and its double-cover SU(2).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Indeed, rotations act on the two-dimensional sphere, and thus also on **H***ℓ* by function composition $\psi \mapsto \psi \circ \rho ^{-1}$ for ψ a spherical harmonic and ρ a rotation.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The representation **H***ℓ* is an irreducible representation of SO(3).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The elements of **H***ℓ* arise as the restrictions to the sphere of elements of **A***ℓ*: harmonic polynomials homogeneous of degree ℓ on three-dimensional Euclidean space **R**3.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Thus as an irreducible representation of SO(3), **H***ℓ* is isomorphic to the space of traceless symmetric tensors of degree ℓ.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, the analogous statements hold in higher dimensions: the space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics on the n-sphere is the irreducible representation of SO(*n*+1) corresponding to the traceless symmetric ℓ-tensors.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] However, whereas every irreducible tensor representation of SO(2) and SO(3) is of this kind, the special orthogonal groups in higher dimensions have additional irreducible representations that do not arise in this manner.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The special orthogonal groups have additional spin representations that are not tensor representations, and are *typically* not spherical harmonics.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] An exception are the spin representation of SO(3): strictly speaking these are representations of the double cover SU(2) of SO(3).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] In turn, SU(2) is identified with the group of unit quaternions, and so coincides with the 3-sphere.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The spaces of spherical harmonics on the 3-sphere are certain spin representations of SO(3), with respect to the action by quaternionic multiplication.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be separated into two sets of functions.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] One is hemispherical harmonics (HSH), orthogonal and complete on hemisphere.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] Another is complementary hemispherical harmonics (CHSH).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The angle-preserving symmetries of the two-sphere are described by the group of Möbius transformations PSL(2,**C**).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] With respect to this group, the sphere is equivalent to the usual Riemann sphere.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The group PSL(2,**C**) is isomorphic to the (proper) Lorentz group, and its action on the two-sphere agrees with the action of the Lorentz group on the celestial sphere in Minkowski space.
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] The analog of the spherical harmonics for the Lorentz group is given by the hypergeometric series; furthermore, the spherical harmonics can be re-expressed in terms of the hypergeometric series, as SO(3) = PSU(2) is a subgroup of PSL(2,**C**).
[src:spherical-harmonics/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, hypergeometric series can be generalized to describe the symmetries of any symmetric space; in particular, hypergeometric series can be developed for any Lie group.
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] In mathematics, **vector spherical harmonics** (**VSH**) are an extension of the scalar spherical harmonics for use with vector fields.
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] The components of the VSH are complex-valued functions expressed in the spherical coordinate basis vectors.
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] Several conventions have been used to define the VSH.
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] with ${\hat {\mathbf {r} }}$ being the unit vector along the radial direction in spherical coordinates and $\mathbf {r}$ the vector along the radial direction with the same norm as the radius, i.e., $\mathbf {r} =r{\hat {\mathbf {r} }}$ .
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] The radial factors are included to guarantee that the dimensions of the VSH are the same as those of the ordinary spherical harmonics and that the VSH do not depend on the radial spherical coordinate.
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] The labels on the components reflect that $E_{\ell m}^{r}$ is the radial component of the vector field, while $E_{\ell m}^{(1)}$ and $E_{\ell m}^{(2)}$ are transverse components (with respect to the radius vector $\mathbf {r}$ ).
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] Because vector bosons such as the photon are spin-one, the vector spherical harmonics are commonly used in physics to describe vector and pseudovector interactions, such as electromagnetic transitions, in atomic and nuclear systems.
[src:spherical-harmonics/vector-spherical-harmonics] They are a special ( ${\textstyle s=1}$ ) case of the spin spherical harmonics.
